#### Issue details
When creating a TextButton with a TextButtonStyle, it is possible to provide pressedOffsetY. When pressing the Button, the Button Image is changed to the provided down Drawable and the Label should be moved by the value of pressedOffsetY.
That part works. But when releasing the button, the Label does not move back. (Button is NOT checked). This does not happen, when only a Drawable for up is provided.
Happens with JSON and in Code.

#### Reproduction steps/code

```java
TextButton tb = new TextButton("test", skin, "default");
stage.addActor(tb);
```
With JSON provided Style:

this works as expected:
```json
"com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.ui.TextButton$TextButtonStyle": {
    "default":            {"font": "font16", "pressedOffsetY": -1.0},
  },
```

this too:

```json
"com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.ui.TextButton$TextButtonStyle": {
    "default":            {"font": "font16",  "up": "label-bg-sandstone", "pressedOffsetY": -1.0},
  },
```

but this doesn't:
```json
"com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.ui.TextButton$TextButtonStyle": {
    "default":            {"font": "font16",  "down": "label-bg-sandstone-down", "up": "label-bg-sandstone", "pressedOffsetY": -1.0},
  },
```


and in Code:

this works:
```java
TextButtonStyle tbs = new TextButtonStyle(null, null, null, new BitmapFont());

TextButton tb = new TextButton("test", tbs);
stage.addActor(tb);
```

this does not:
```java
Drawable up = skin.getDrawable("label-bg-sandstone");
Drawable down = skin.getDrawable("label-bg-sandstone-down");
TextButtonStyle tbs = new TextButtonStyle(up, down, null, new BitmapFont());

TextButton tb = new TextButton("test", tbs);
stage.addActor(tb);
```

#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies
1.9.4 and 1.9.6

#### Please select the affected platforms
- [ x] Android
- [ ] iOS (robovm)
- [ ] iOS (MOE)
- [ ] HTML/GWT
- [ x] Windows
- [ x] Linux
- [ ] MacOS

In the source for the Input interface

/** @return The rate of rotation around the x axis. (rad/s) */
public float getAccelerometerX ();

/** @return The rate of rotation around the y axis. (rad/s) */
public float getAccelerometerY ();

/** @return The rate of rotation around the z axis. (rad/s) */
public float getAccelerometerZ ();

public float getGyroscopeX ();

public float getGyroscopeY ();

public float getGyroscopeZ ();

In the AndroidInput.java implementation of this interface, getAccelerometer returns values from the event Sensor.TYPE_ACCELEROMETER which returns acceleration in m/s^2 on an axis, not rotation.

In short, the javadocs should be moved to the getGyroscope functions to be correct

#### Issue details
Images with an alpha gradient display banding when loaded as part of an atlas. The top image is the region from an `TextureAtlas`. The bottom image is the same png loaded as a `Texture`.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6973062/23950815/2e0b3390-0984-11e7-8df0-5bff1afddef0.png)

Related to [issue 3782](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/issues/3782)

#### Reproduction steps/code

Atlas files attached.

    public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
        SpriteBatch batch;
        private TextureAtlas.AtlasRegion cloudRegion;
        private Texture cloudTexture;

        @Override
        public void create() {
            batch = new SpriteBatch();
            TextureAtlas atlas = new TextureAtlas(Gdx.files.internal("background-pack.txt"));
            cloudRegion = atlas.findRegion("cloud");
            cloudTexture = new Texture("background-pack-1.png");
        }

        @Override
        public void render() {
            Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0, 0, 0, 0);
            Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

            batch.begin();
            batch.setBlendFunction(GL20.GL_ONE, GL20.GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA);
            batch.draw(cloudTexture,
                    0,
                    0);

            batch.draw(cloudRegion,
                    0,
                    cloudTexture.getHeight());


            batch.end();
        }
    }

