#### Issue details
Frequently, the frequency at which touchDragged events can be triggered on iOS seems to drop to 30Hz, even if graphics are rendering at 60fps. It can make the framerate of an app feel slow, even though the rendering isn't the problem.

It appears somewhat random whether or not the events come at ~30 or 60 "frames per second".

It seems to be a known challenge, even beyond libgdx: https://forums.developer.apple.com/thread/62315

#### Reproduction steps/code
Move a Sprite 1:1 with a touch.

Count touch events via:

```
boolean processedTouch;
float nextFrameTouchCountSave = 1f;
int frameTouchCountPerSecond;
int frameTouchRunningCount;

@Override ... touchDragged(...) {
  processedTouch = true;
}

draw() {
  // Check if any touchDragged events were passed since the last draw()
  if (processedTouch) {
    processedTouch = false;
    frameTouchRunningCount++;
  }

  nextFrameTouchCountSave -= deltaTime;
  if (nextFrameTouchCountSave <= 0f) {
    // We've counted for 1 second. Save the current running count, and start a new count.
    frameTouchCountPerSecond = frameTouchRunningCount;
    frameTouchRunningCount = 0;
    nextFrameTouchCountSave += 1f;
  }
}
```

Constantly drag the object in circles on your iPhone.

See that "frameTouchCountPerSecond" could sometimes be ~30, sometimes ~60, *even if* Gdx.graphics.getFramesPerSecond() returns 60.

#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies
1.9.6

#### Please select the affected platforms
iOS (robovm)
